node.text:
i was stuck in this cycle for years and years. avoiding behaviors became a rigid habit because i felt temporary relief when i successfully avoided the cause of my anxiety. but it’s been empowering to take control of my anxiety. just last week i had a meltdown because i had scheduled to get a contraceptive implant and medical stuff trigger anxiety for me. i cried and cried and almost cancelled but decided to face my fears. and as it usually goes, it was all good in the end and it wasn’t NEARLY as bad as my anxiety had made it out to be. afterwards i felt very proud of myself for doing the scary thing anyway. and next time i have to get a new one, i probably won’t feel anxious about it, so that’s a win !! i view anxiety as a faulty switch in my brain, and it’s up to me to rewire it to give me a more healthy response to stressful situations. generalized anxiety disorder isn’t easy, it makes everything hard because everyday things make me severely anxious. but every time i face my anxiety, i like to imagine it growing smaller, and releasing the grasp on my life a little more each time. i started with small things, like asking for help in a store, or answering the phone to someone i didn’t know very well. things that i wanted to be able to do but felt anxious about. and once i could do those things without having severe anxiety, i would try something a little more difficult. and wow, life is so much richer now, and i feel a lot more independent than i did at my worst. i still have GAD, but i’m proud of myself for challenging it every chance i can ! have you faced your anxiety lately ? 

#mentalhealth #anxiety #crazyheadcomics

node.text:
for the longest time i felt like i was broken beyond repair and that everything was unfixable, but as i started my recovery journey i realized that all the fragments of me, each individual piece of me was still there, just in a disarray. not broken, just jumbled and all mixed up. i just had to figure out how to put everything together again in a way that fits 👍🏻

#mentalhealth #crazyheadcomics

node.text:
today is suicide prevention day. as some of you may know, i’m a suicide attempt survivor, about 6 years has passed since my attempt, but it still makes me uncomfortable to talk about. not because i feel ashamed of what i did in a moment of despair and desperation, but because everyone i love follows me on here and i know that it was traumatic for them as well as me, so i feel weird reminding them of this part of my past sometimes. but i’m putting aside that discomfort for now because this is so important. if i had died all those years ago, i would have missed so many moments i cherish. during my attempt, i was psychotic, felt like a failure, freshly traumatized from going through things i’m still not comfortable sharing with everyone. i was self harming and it was the lowest point in my life, i didn’t see a way out. suicide is NOT selfish, suicidal thoughts and actions are symptoms of severe mental anguish, it’s about wanting the pain to stop because it’s unbearable. i was seventeen and i wasn’t prepared to deal with my mental illnesses and the effects it had on my life. but i thank the stars and the universe everyday that i am still here. life isn’t perfect and i’m still dealing with pain and mental illness and it’s a struggle, but it did get better. if this can make anyone stay a little longer, or reconsider their plans to leave, it would mean everything. i can’t imagine not being here, not feeling the sun on my face or listening to my favorite music or growing a plant from a little seed. the little things help me a lot. life is hard and challenging and it feels lonely and sometimes not worth all the pain, but there is so much meaning and hope if we’re willing to stay for a little longer. i promise you, life can always get better, but you’re taking that option away when you attempt to end your life. i didn’t see a way out of my misery but time really can heal a lot of wounds. stay another day, find one thing to hold onto and cling to it. the world will NOT be the same without you, you matter and there’s so much love waiting for you. please stay. 

#suicideprevention #suicidepreventionmonth #suicidepreventionday #mentalhealth

node.text:
my goal with this account is to have conversations about mental health where nobody feels judged or misrepresented. but i always notice an influx of stigmatizing comments and DMs every time I mention things like personality disorders and substance abuse. i made a post about bpd a while back and some of the responses i got were not very nice - lots of “watch out for people with bpd, they’re abusers !!” and things like that. this makes me sad and it’s important to remember that just because you had a bad experience with someone with a certain mental illness, it does not mean that everyone with that illness will behave like that person you knew. let’s not pretend like all mentally ill people are the same. let’s see us all as individuals with our own unique stories and experiences. let’s make sure that we don’t make someone feel bad about their mental health condition while reading comments on a mental health page !!! sorry if this was confusing i’m post-migraine and have the biggest brain fog haha. i just want everyone to be kind to each other ! instead of comparing or assuming, let’s listen and learn about all the different ways mental illness can manifest in different people 

#crazyheadcomics #mentalhealth

node.text:
i think the mental illness symptom that made me realize that something was wrong was feeling unhappy anywhere and everywhere. i could be doing my favorite thing, with my favorite people, but my brain didn’t give me that regular happy feeling. instead of excitement, it was indifference. instead of happiness, it was dread. instead of contentment, it was severe boredom. everything that used to be fun was just gray and dull. nothing mattered anymore. depression be like that. i didn’t really have a closing point or advice to go with this caption, i just wanted to draw this feeling 

#mentalhealth #crazyheadcomics

node.text:
trying to remind myself that my interests, passions and hobbies are still there and can wait for me to get back to them during times of stress or depression. i have a BUNCH of things that i absolutely love doing, but when mental illness acts up, it’s hard to feel motivated to do them, which makes me feel like i’m only faking my interests and i don’t actually find things fun or entertaining :( but hobbies should be fun and if they’re not giving you the joy they typically give you, then maybe it’s a sign that you should take a moment to rest or evaluate the stressors in your life. i’m trying to walk the fine line of not forcing myself to do things if i’m not enjoying it, but also not giving up completely on the things that i typically enjoy just because mental illness can make fun things feel like nothing. do you relate to this, and if so, how do you cope with it ? 

#mentalhealth #crazyheadcomics

node.text:
i was a bit late in receiving my ADHD diagnosis, so i only begun to understand the way my brain work as a young adult. learning about my neurodivergency has been freeing, and starting to work WITH my adhd rather than against it has made my life a LOT easier. if i have a project that i have to finish i’ll think of something to reward myself with after i’m done, to motivate me to complete my task !! everything i own has a designated place, so i never lose anything!! i sacrificed a higher paying job to taking a  chance with my art, and becoming my own boss because i couldn’t handle the stress and needed a break ! so now i can make my own schedule !! having adhd can definitely come with a lot of challenges, but it’s been great to figure out solutions to my challenges so i can live peacefully with my adhd diagnosis 🥳 what is the biggest challenge of having adhd to you, and do you have any lifehacks or tips that could be useful to people with adhd ? 

#mentalhealth #adhd #crazyheadcomics

node.text:
my august has been pretty shaky so far and i haven’t really been feeling motivated, but i’ve been trying to implement more healthy habits and routines that make things easier for myself. i always keep a water bottle in the fridge so i remember to drink water, i do the dishes right after i cook so they don’t pile up as much, i write my to do lists on little post it notes broken down into smaller steps so i can tick all the little steps off and feel like i’m accomplishing something. I’m growing herbs and plants to feel like i’m taking care of something that needs me. life is hard sometimes but i keep remind myself that i can make my days a bit better by taking a little walk or calling someone or cooking something i’ve never cooked before. by watching youtube how to videos and not being on my phone as much, and not overextending myself on social media, like i used to do often. the rest of this month is all about positive mental health habits for me 😌 

#mentalhealth #crazyheadcomics
